    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if L1 actually sets them to zero, it's basically doing feature selection for you? why does the math work out that way for L1 but not for L2? like what's happening with the optimization part?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That’s right! L1 regularization has a special property where it tends to make some weights exactly zero, which can lead to feature selection because those coefficients represent unit interactions with the selected features. This happens due to the absolute value in the L1 penalty term, which creates a characteristic \"V-shape\" or \"L-shape\" objective function landscape. When optimizing (typically using methods like gradient descent or coordinate descent), L1 can pass through the origin (0,0) and find a point with zero coefficients alongside a minimal penalty, a phenomenon not possible with the quadratic L2 penalty. L2, on the other hand, always adds a positive penalty that encourages all weights to be reduced uniformly, thus never exactly reaching zero. The optimization heavily involves calculus of variations and constrained optimization, focusing on combining coefficient shrinkage with the prediction error.",
      "source": "target",
