      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so the shape of the penalty is the key. can you give me a more intuitive way to think about it? i'm struggling to visualize how that \"v-shape\" versus the parabola actually forces the coefficients to hit zero in L1 but just keeps them small in L2.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Visualizing it, imagine you're trying to minimize the cost while keeping the path your weights take (their values during optimization) as large as possible without increasing the cost too much. With an L1 penalty, you can sharply turn away from zero, but if you keep moving away too far, the cost suddenly shoots up – that sharp turn is a magnet that pulls it back to zero. L2 penalty, however, gently curves back if you stray from zero. You can sway away and then back, but you're never forced to rest at zero's edge. Essentially, in L1, zero is like the lowest valley, suitable for your route, while for L2, it's just one of many shallow dips along a gentle uphill.",
      "source": "target",
